Commentary.Commentary: Back for the chase. The players are out in the middle. Craig Overton to bowl first. Will Jacks and Tawanda Muyeye to open.
...THE CHASE...

This is definitely not a 180 pitch but not a 133 wicket as well. Southern Brave would have loved 15-20 runs more. They never got back on track after losing the top half for not much. Jordan Thompson played a small cameo along with Hilton Cartwright late in the innings but never really got into the game. Oval Invincibles will be confident but they will be up against the likes of Jofra Archer and Tymal Mills. Can they chase it down? Stay tuned to find out.

Rashid Khan is up for a chat. He feels it is not an easy wicket to bat on and thinks they could chase it down. Mentions he got hit for five sixes last time on this ground and is happy to end with three wickets today. Ends by saying he accepts good and bad the same way to be successful.

Oval Invincibles have executed their plans to perfection. The pitch was on the slower side and got some turn in it as well. Jason Behrendorff bowled with precision and got both the openers. Rashid Khan in his first five balls struck thrice to put Southern Brave under tremendous pressure. The batting team did get some momentum for a small period but Sam Curran with his slower dipping full tosses made amends and ended with three wickets.

A fantastic bowling display from Oval Invincibles and they have done justice to the thought of bowling first. They would have taken the score at the start and will be confident right now going into the chase.

TOSS - Oval Invincibles have won the toss and will BOWL.

Oval Invincibles, on the other hand, are riding high after their impressive 83-run win over Welsh Fire. Jordan Cox's blistering 86 off 29 deliveries and Will Jacks' 38 set the tone for their massive 226/4 score. Tom Curran's four-wicket haul and Jason Behrendorff's three wickets further sealed the win. With players like Sam Curran, who's taken seven wickets and scored 62 runs, and Rashid Khan in their lineup, Oval Invincibles seem confident of extending their winning streak. Given their past performance and current form, they might have an edge over Southern Brave

Southern Brave will be looking to bounce back after their last loss to Trent Rockets. Leus du Plooy's half-century and contributions from Jason Roy, James Coles, and Michael Bracewell were notable in their previous match, but ultimately weren't enough to secure a win. With a passionate home crowd and James Vince's experienced leadership, Southern Brave will aim to capitalize on their home advantage and put up a strong fight against the Invincibles.

Get ready for an exciting match at The Rose Bowl in Southampton as defending champions Oval Invincibles take on Southern Brave in Match 19 of The Hundred Men's 2025! The Invincibles are currently leading the points table with three wins from four matches, while Southern Brave sit fourth with two wins and two losses.
...MATCH DAY...

The Hundred, 2025, is entering its crunch phase, and the points table is tighter than ever. With three teams locked on 12 points, the chase for a top-three finish is turning into a fierce sprint. Match 19 takes us to the Rose Bowl in Southampton, where Southern Brave welcome Oval Invincibles for a clash that could reshape the standings. Both sides are nestled in the top half of the ladder, and for the Brave, currently sitting on 8 points, this is a must-win to stay in the hunt. They burst out of the gates with two commanding victories, but a couple of stumbles since then have left them needing to rediscover their rhythm. Southern Brave’s campaign so far has followed a clear pattern - success while chasing, but stumbles when setting a target. Leus du Plooy has been the standout performer with the bat, the only Brave batter to breach the 100-run mark this season. Jason Roy has offered glimpses of his firepower, while James Coles has quietly chipped in with useful contributions. But the real concern lies with James Vince. With the skipper averaging just 15 in four games, this has left a noticeable void at the top. He’ll be eager to find form and lend some much-needed stability to the top order. So far, the Brave have managed just one fifty-plus opening stand, a telling sign of their struggle to lay solid foundations for the middle order to build upon. With the ball, Brave’s pace arsenal, led by Tymal Mills and Jofra Archer, has shown promise, but hasn’t quite delivered in crunch situations of late. The inability to close out key moments has cost them, and Chris Jordan's lack of impact has only added to their woes.
